text.tspan: To confirm vessel`s compliance with actions required in case of Heavy Weather Damage, please refer to Section 4 ‘EmergencyProcedures’ of the Emergency Contingency and Planning Manual.2) To appoint a salvage company if considered necessary.3) Assess extent of damage to vessel and/or it’s equipment and make arrangement for necessary repairs/renewal.4) If cargo is affected notify the charterers through the owners.5) If the vessel diverts or seeks port of refuge, general average to be declared.6) Arrange for superintendent to travel to attend the vessel.7) Guide the vessel to minimize further damage by providing latest weather update.7.5.15MAN OVERBOARDTo confirm vessel`s compliance with actions required incase of Man overboard, please refer to Section 4 ‘Emergency Procedures’ ofthe Emergency Contingency and Planning Manual.2) Notify the owners, flag authority and P&I club.3) If deviation is likely to be extensive, inform charterers.4) Notify next of kin.5) In case the person is not located, to take a decision in consultation with the search and rescue organisation as to when the searchis to be abandoned taking into consideration all the relevant data obtained from the ship.7.6OFFICE DUTY/PROCEDURE WHEN IN RECEIPT OF SSAS ALERTWhen activated the ship security alert system shall initiate and transmit a ship-to-shore security alert to a competent authoritydesignated by the Administration, identifying the ship, its location and indicating that the security of the ship is under threat or it hasbeen compromised. The system will not raise any alarm on-board the ship. The ship security alert system shall be capable of being activated from thenavigation bridge and in at least one other location. The switch should not conspicuous.Keep Owners informed contact local authorities through ship’s agent for any further assistance.7.7SITUATION REPORT (SITREP)Incident Commander must publish status report on a pre-determined timeframe depending upon incident using ‘Situation Report(SitRep)’. Initially the target for the first SitRep is within one hour of mobilizing the ‘Incident Command System’ (ICS). Thereafter theIncident Commander will determine an appropriate schedule for issuance.Incident Commander is responsible for preparing the SitRep. It is reviewed by the ‘Insurance Team’ and/ or ‘Media Team’ as requiredbefore being released.SitRep must not contain:SpeculationOpinion on or attribution of, causation or liabilityViews on the action of company or other partiesUnverified factsConfidential information The list of recipients will depend entirely on the stakeholders involved in an incident and may include both internal and externalstakeholders.7.8LIST OF CONTACTS7.8.1CONTACT DETAILS1.CONTACT DETAILS OF OFFICE STAFFContact details of office staff are available in the company’s web based ship report and monitoring software ‘PHOENIX’ and alsoprovided in hard copy in the ERT headquarters located on the 21st floor at Company’s head office.2. EXTERNAL CONTACT DETAILSContact Details for Flag, Class, P & I Clubs, Media and Legal consultants, salvage and towage etc are available in the company’s webbased ship report and monitoring software ‘PHOENIX’ and also provided in hard copy in the ERT headquarters located on the 21stfloor at Company’s head office.7.9MEDIA HANDLING7.9.1MEDIA SPOKESPERSON/ MEDIA RELEASE
